1 The important questions

1.1 Dependent variables (DV)

According to Dollinger:

Wichtig neben der âway of speakingâ und âdistinct Englishâ question ist mir die âHave your heard of the term Standard Canadian English?â [Frage]

1.2 Independent variables (IV)

According to Dollinger:

  • region,
  • education,
  • age, and
  • gender.

1.3 Method

Something on the more pedestrian side to begin with: a regression with the different values of the DV as outcome.

1.3.1 Ordinal logistic regression using only one variable as outcome

Letâs start with the first of the DVs, cdn_way. Here are our responses:

# A tibble: 5 Ã 2

To preprocess the data, we will

  • eliminate NA cases and
  • filter out non-Canadian respondents.

Because the cdn_way variable has levels that are ordered we will convert it into type int and sort the values properly.

# A tibble: 4 Ã 2
  cdn_way_num     n
        <dbl> <int>
1           1    37
2           2   194
3           3  1211

Ensure that the DV is an ordinal factor and other important variables are factors as well.

1.5 Model term viz

Visualize the model terms. One approach is to plot each model term individually, like so for gender:

It actually looks like gender is a pretty boring predictor!

But this is not too useful, since we want to compare predictors. So now we try to plot all the model terms.

Application values
For each predictor, one of the levels is not visualized. Thatâs the application value. So for gender, female is not shown. This means that the odds ratio for female is right on the dotted line (the model intercept), the other two values in the gender factor (male and other) are shown to the extent that they increase or decrease the chance of a higher rating in the response variable.
Which level of a factor is the application value?
Itâs the one thatâs first in the alphabet (cf.Â female > male > other).

Among Canadian respondents, the factor edu_comp has by far the most predictive power.
Among the regions, QC and BC stand out as particularly pessimistic, with statistical significance.
Note: while regionpe also looks at first glance like it might be interesting, it is not, since there are so few responses and there is no significance.

In the spirit of a minimal adequate model, it would be best to drop the terms gender and age from the model entirely, since their predictions are weak and statistically insignificant.
